{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NUu2WYVMfEn1TZCueCpyDu","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I can see the bug now. In `LinkReferences::visit(Reference& ope)`:\n\n1. First it checks if the reference name matches a macro parameter and sets `found_param = true`.\n2. Then it UNCONDITIONALLY checks the grammar for a matching rule, and if found, sets `ope.rule_` even when the reference is a macro parameter.\n\nThis is the bug: when `found_param` is true (i.e., the reference is a macro parameter name like `D`), the code should NOT also link it to the global rule `D`. If the parameter name collides with a global rule name, it sets both `ope.iarg_` (pointing to the macro parameter) and `ope.rule_` (pointing to the global rule `D`).\n\n\nThen during parsing, when `Reference::parse` gets called, it prioritizes the `rule_` field and uses the global rule instead of the macro parameter, which is the wrong behavior. Let me check the `Reference::parse` function to confirm this is where the issue manifests.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":853,"cache_read_input_tokens":25689,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":853},"output_tokens":39,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b7007705-6449-4a1c-9631-ae2adc6d93b5","uuid":"188486c9-c45b-4882-9321-2223cafd1c72"}
